As shown in 
, the combination of zinc centers and BTC3− groups forms a 2D three-connecting bilayered structure. And further through L ligand, these 2D bilayers are integrated together to form a 3D layer-pillared net [
]. Note that herein the L ligands not only act as pillars to support the 2D bilayered net, but also they are deeply embedded in the bilayered net, playing the penetrating role, thus resulting in the overall 3D self-penetrating net. Furthermore, the volume of void space (occupied by DMF and [Me2NH2]+ ions) observed in polymer 1 is estimated by Platon program, giving 1684.5Å3, equal to 33.0% of the cell volume, indicating potential porous framework of it .

Topologically, if Zn(II) centers and the BTC3−units are viewed to be the 4- and 3-connected nodes, respectively, [
] and then this framework becomes a (3,4)-connected net with (6·82)(6·85)(62
·10)(62
·83
·10) topology built on four-connecting metal centers and three-connecting organic nodes. In the literature, there are a large number of (3, 4)-connected net such as Pt3O4, jph, C3N4, and twisted boracite net . In contrast to them, the present topology matrix is obviously different and holds self-penetrating motif that is still very rare in the literature. Moreover, the self-penetrating manner is described as catenations of the eight-membered circuits and ten-membered circuits [
].
